\section{Summary}

Quantitative analysis of DCE-MRI and DWI data requires a series of processing steps,
including pre-processing of MR signal, voxel-wise curve fitting, and post-processing, 
i.e., statistical analysis of kinetic parameters from a series of scans. \pkg{dcemriS4}
provides a comprehensive set of functions for pre-processing and for modelling 
DCE-MRI and DWI data.

A (nearly) complete pipeline for the analysis of DCE-MRI and DWI data can be established
using R. Raw images from the MR scanner are typically provided in DICOM format and can 
be converted into NIfTI format using \pkg{oro.dicom} \cite{oro.dicom}. Using 
\pkg{dcemriS4} dynamic $T_1$ acquisitions can be converted into voxel-wise contrast 
agent concentration time curves. A variety of kinetic models and models for the
arterial input function is provided. Point estimates for kinetic parameters can be 
achived in a fast and robust manner using either least-squares or maximum a posterior
inference, and information on the uncertainty in the estimates can be gained
from the Bayesian MCMC algorithm, e.g., by looking at standard errors, credible 
intervals or even the whole posterior distribution.

\pkg{dcemriS4} utilizes the \code{NIfTI} class defined in the \pkg{oro.nifti} package.
This allows to retain meta information stored in an image, e.g., patient id or scan
date, when performing an analysis. In addition, each step in the analysis pipeline
can be recorded using the audit trail option provided by \pkg{oro.nifti}. Hence,
results can easily be reproduced and errors in the analysis can be found more rapid.

To our knowledge, \pkg{dcemriS4} is the only freely available software package
for analysis of DCE-MRI and DWI data \textbf{???}. It is available from the R projects 
CRAN page and from \url{http://www.dcemri.org} and is released under BSD license.


